Waltzing Across the Floor
1.  Waltz forward facing forward.  Repeat waltzing backwards.
2.  Waltz from side to side moving forward.
3.  Waltz facing eachother 123, then back to back123.
4.  serpentine with a partner:
    - cross arms, cross left foot over right foot waltzing towards the right 123,
                          cross right foot over left foot waltzing towards the left 123.
5.  The Square formation:
    - Partners face in opposite directions holding inside hands.
    - Beginning with inside legs,waltz 123, 123, (one partner is waltzing forward as the other is waltzing backwards)
    - Turn a half turn in the direction of your partner waltzing 123, then another half turn waltzing 123.
    - Now you are facing in the opposite direction, waltz 123, 123 and continue as above.

"These hands have touched so many,  Marion's hands.  In recent years, students have been drawn to Marion Rosen and to her work.  An institute has developed to support it and to provide training in the Rosen Method of bodywork.  Here you see Marion doing a demonstration in one of the training classes at the Rosen Institute in Berkeley, California.  Many of the students watching will go on to complete the three year training program and become Rosen work practitioners.
In August of 1983, a few students gathered in Marion's home to hear her tell her story, the story of the evolution of a life's work.  This video tape is for all of us whose lives she's touched."
Paula Kimbro https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OPfbcP9-wKg

On The Floor
Introduction
Relaxing, allowing, opening, inward attention, and awareness
Teacher's words are very important
Tone of voice, important to be heard
Arc and flow of the class leads into this section
Slow, quiet, inward music.
--Classical works well; avoid spacy music;
--music that allows and doesn't have a specific agenda;
--words may, or may not, work
Great for the mobility of the spine especially.
Classic Movements ( some are listed here)
Lying on back:
Hip Rock with one knee to chest , alternate legs
Hip Rock with straight leg, flexed at hip, alternate legs
Bent knees falling to one side, as head rotates in opposite direction, repeat in opposite direction
Pelvic Lift: lifting pubic bone upwards, keeping buttocks soft as knees are moved away from you
Pelvic Rock: Slowly rocking pelvis towards the head and towards the feet.
Side position:
Long Straight Legs Lift, the lift is from the abdomen
On all Four's:
Child's Pose

I'm skipping class tonight to support my fellow Rising Phoenix Integrative Medicine Center collaborator at the Commonwealth Club tonight:  Michael F. Cantwell, MD, MPH; Author, Map of the Spirit: Diagnosis and Treatment of the Spirit

Map of the Spirit presents a radically new, universal framework of human spiritual development — the process by which we construct then live out our spiritual beliefs. Cantwell says that all of us, regardless of our particular spiritual beliefs, pass through the same four stages of spiritual development; "blockages" in this process give rise to “spiritual stress,” the spiritual roots of ill-health and disease. Using his book's questionnaire-based framework, he says anyone can determine, quickly and easily: 1) how much spirituality is affecting their health, 2) where they are in the course of their spiritual development, and 3) how to treat their spirits and their “spiritual stress.”

Cantwell's book just won the 2013 USA Best Book Award for Health: Alternative Medicine.

- See more at: http://www.commonwealthclub.org/events/2014-01-28/healing-body-healing-spirit#sthash.lCftTqgC.dpuf

June 4, 2006 By Debra J. Thiesen, Movement Teacher Training Graduate and Advanced Bodywork Student Last October a group of us embarked on an eight-month Rosen Movement Teacher Training at the Berkeley Center.  We started each day of the weekly training by coming together in circle for movement lead by Theresa Garcia, Kate O’Shea and Donna Meehan.  The last week of May, we concluded our journey the same way.  As we started warm-up to “Come Away With Me” by Eva Cassidy, the tears flowed.  We were graciously lead by example to invite and allow the movement to move us.  The space was fertile to explore our inner landscape.  All were taken in and touched. In January, as the movement deepened within me, I made an interesting discovery that I was not expecting to find.  My original intention for the movement class, which was to support my study of Rosen Bodywork, had shifted.  The vision of a practice as a Movement Teacher emerged!  In the months that followed, I have related the natural flow of the components of the movements to our human development.  It seems the hourly movement class traces our life cycle!  This affords all those who participate in it the possibility for healing any aspect of their development while returning more authentically to their true nature.  This understanding strengthens my desire to share it with others. My metaphoric parallel is as follows: Warm-up as to our youth: We stand in circle but move alone finding our rhythm.  We stretch our wings only near our core and are aligned with the heart as the center of our being and feel the beat as it pumps.  We fill our lungs with air as our chests open as we take small steps to give our legs and hip joints a view of their possibilities. Stretching as to our young adult life: We explore our reaching-out muscles, more end-range movements, and yawns are welcome.  The rib cage explores its possibilities allowing the breath to flow; senses are heightened in expanded awareness of the heaven and earth in us.  With elongation, we courageously move out from our hearts to take in others. Circle as to our adult life:  We are shakers and movers of the large muscles of our legs, pelvis and hip joints.  Our breath and heartbeats quicken.  The stepping is complex and faster, this prepares us for the dancing to come.  Now we take hands in our circle, feeling the support and energy of community as we find our collective and individual balances. Across-the-floor as to our mid-life:  We are prepared through the movements of the previous components to partner with another.  We move across the floor in deeper connectedness to lively music and laughter.  All the body is engaged in dance; through grace and creativity, our lungs and heart are fully functioning. We are joyful, alive and do not want it to end! On-the-floor as to our elderly life: Our breath and heartbeat slows down and becomes fuller as we welcome the support of the floor and rest.  There is time for reflection.  Spinal movements are the focus; the pace is more our own.  Small movements go deeper into the body bringing awareness.  With this relaxation, we enjoy the freedom of our flexibility and respect our limitations.  We are prepared for transition and to meet whatever comes next. I am grateful to be part of both aspects of the Rosen Method.  I look forward to the future of the movement and sharing it with others.
